{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":920,"text":"Tonight, I'm going to share with you\nmy passion for science."},{"time":4560,"text":"I'm not talking about science\nthat takes baby steps."},{"time":7600,"text":"I'm talking about science\nthat takes enormous leaps."},{"time":11880,"text":"I'm talking Darwin, I'm talking Einstein,"},{"time":15280,"text":"I'm talking revolutionary science\nthat turns the world on its head."},{"time":19440,"text":"In a moment, I'm going to talk\nabout two ideas that might do this."},{"time":23800,"text":"I say \"might\""},{"time":25040,"text":"because, with revolutionary ideas,\nmost are flat wrong,"},{"time":27840,"text":"and even those that are right\nseldom have the impact"},{"time":30320,"text":"that we want them to have."}]},{"cues":[{"time":32040,"text":"To explain why I picked\ntwo ideas in particular,"},{"time":34560,"text":"I'm going to start with a mystery."},{"time":36840,"text":"1847, Vienna, Austria."},{"time":41080,"text":"Ignaz Semmelweis was a somber,\ncompulsively thorough doctor"},{"time":44720,"text":"who ran two maternity clinics."},{"time":46600,"text":"They were identical except for one thing."},{"time":49720,"text":"Women were dying of high fevers\nsoon after giving birth"},{"time":52400,"text":"three times more often\nat one of the clinics than at the other."},{"time":56600,"text":"Trying to figure out\nwhat the difference was that caused this,"},{"time":59560,"text":"Semmelweis looked at everything he could."},{"time":61600,"text":"Sanitation? No."},{"time":63360,"text":"Medical procedures? No."},{"time":66000,"text":"Air flow? No."}]},{"cues":[{"time":68800,"text":"The puzzle went unsolved\nuntil he happened to autopsy a doctor"},{"time":72080,"text":"who died of an infected scalpel cut."},{"time":74760,"text":"The doctor's symptoms were identical\nto those of the mothers who were dying."},{"time":78560,"text":"How was that possible?"},{"time":79960,"text":"How could a male doctor\nget the same thing as new mothers?"},{"time":83560,"text":"Semmelweis reconstructed\neverything the doctor had done"},{"time":86840,"text":"right before he got sick,"},{"time":88120,"text":"and he discovered\nthat he'd been autopsying a corpse."},{"time":92440,"text":"Had something gotten\nin his wound that killed him?"},{"time":96760,"text":"With growing excitement,"},{"time":98560,"text":"Semmelweis looked\nfor any connection he could"},{"time":101400,"text":"between dead bodies in the morgue\nand dead mothers in his delivery room,"},{"time":106800,"text":"and he found it."},{"time":109320,"text":"It turned out that at the hospital\nwith the high death rate,"},{"time":112200,"text":"but not the others,"},{"time":114000,"text":"doctors delivered babies immediately\nafter autopsying corpses in the morgue."},{"time":119160,"text":"Aha! Corpses were contaminating\nthe doctors' hands"},{"time":123120,"text":"and killing his mothers."},{"time":125240,"text":"So he ordered the doctors\nto sterilize their hands,"},{"time":128320,"text":"and the deaths stopped."},{"time":131400,"text":"Dr. Ignaz Semmelweis\nhad discovered infectious disease."}]},{"cues":[{"time":136400,"text":"But the doctors of the day\nthought he was crazy,"},{"time":139840,"text":"because they knew,\nand had for hundreds of years,"},{"time":143360,"text":"that odorous vapors\ncalled miasmas caused disease,"},{"time":148480,"text":"not these hypothetical particles\nthat you couldn't see."},{"time":152880,"text":"It took 20 years\nfor Frenchman Louis Pasteur"},{"time":157080,"text":"to prove that Semmelweis was right."},{"time":159680,"text":"Pasteur was an agricultural chemist"},{"time":162400,"text":"who tried to figure out\nwhy milk and beer spoiled so often."},{"time":166600,"text":"He found that bacteria were the culprits."},{"time":170160,"text":"He also found that bacteria\ncould kill people in exactly the same way"},{"time":174040,"text":"that Semmelweis's patients were dying."}]},{"cues":[{"time":177120,"text":"We now look at what I want\nto talk about tonight, in two ideas."},{"time":182600,"text":"We saw it with Semmelweis,\nthat he was a revolutionary."},{"time":186560,"text":"He did it for two reasons."},{"time":187840,"text":"One, he opened our eyes\nto a completely new world."},{"time":191720,"text":"We'd known since the 1680s about bacteria."},{"time":194720,"text":"We just didn't know\nthat bacteria killed people."},{"time":197200,"text":"And he also demolished fond ideas\nthat people kept close to their heart."},{"time":202280,"text":"Miasmas didn't kill people.\nBacteria killed people."}]},{"cues":[{"time":206080,"text":"So this brings me to the two ideas\nI want to talk about tonight."},{"time":209440,"text":"One has opened our eyes\nto a completely new universe,"},{"time":212280,"text":"and the other attacks long-held beliefs."}]},{"cues":[{"time":216280,"text":"Let's get started with Dr. Eric Betzig."},{"time":218240,"text":"He's a physicist who has opened our eyes\nto an entirely new world"},{"time":222160,"text":"by violating the laws of physics."},{"time":224720,"text":"Betzig is a true rebel."},{"time":226560,"text":"He quit a job at prestigious\nBell Laboratory"},{"time":229480,"text":"inventing new microscopes for biology"},{"time":231760,"text":"because he thought scientists\nwere taking his brilliant inventions"},{"time":236120,"text":"and doing lousy work with them."},{"time":238880,"text":"So he became a househusband,"},{"time":243360,"text":"but he never lost his passion\nfor figuring out"},{"time":245960,"text":"how to get microscopes\nto see finer and finer details"},{"time":248880,"text":"than had ever been seen before\nor ever could be seen."},{"time":251960,"text":"This is crucial if we're ever\ngoing to understand how cells work,"},{"time":256440,"text":"and how cancer works,"},{"time":257959,"text":"and how something\n150th the size of a head of a pin"},{"time":263400,"text":"can do all these amazing things,"},{"time":265560,"text":"like make proteins"},{"time":267160,"text":"and move charges around"},{"time":269080,"text":"and all of those things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":271400,"text":"There's just one problem."},{"time":274040,"text":"There's this thing\ncalled the law of physics,"},{"time":277040,"text":"and part of the law of physics\nis the thing called the diffraction limit."},{"time":280520,"text":"The diffraction limit is kind of like\nwhen you go to a doctor's office,"},{"time":283920,"text":"you can only see so far down,\nno matter how good glasses you have."}]},{"cues":[{"time":287080,"text":"This was a so-called impossible problem."},{"time":290480,"text":"But one of Betzig's friends\nfigured out how to take a tiny molecule"},{"time":293680,"text":"that was smaller than\nthe best microscope could see"},{"time":296120,"text":"and get it to light up and fluoresce."},{"time":298280,"text":"\"Aha!\" Betzig said."},{"time":300800,"text":"\"I think maybe the laws of physics\nare not so unbreakable after all.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":305520,"text":"So he lashed together a microscope\nin his friend's living room."},{"time":310400,"text":"He had no laboratory."},{"time":312240,"text":"This revolutionary instrument\ngot different protein molecules"},{"time":315840,"text":"to light up in different colors,"},{"time":318080,"text":"and with a computer, he was able\nto turn very, very fuzzy blurs"},{"time":322800,"text":"into very sharp dots and produce images\nof unprecedented and startling clarity."}]},{"cues":[{"time":329520,"text":"For this work, last year,"},{"time":331840,"text":"Eric Betzig won the Nobel Prize."},{"time":335360,"text":"Why?"},{"time":336600,"text":"Because now we can see\nwith unprecedented detail"},{"time":340720,"text":"things that we never had seen before,"},{"time":342560,"text":"and now doctors can get\na better handle on things like cancer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":347080,"text":"But do you think\nBetzig was satisfied there?"},{"time":349600,"text":"No."},{"time":350920,"text":"He wanted movies."},{"time":352800,"text":"The problem was"},{"time":354040,"text":"that even the genius microscopes\nthat he invented were just too slow."},{"time":358040,"text":"So what did he do?"},{"time":359320,"text":"He came up with a 200-year-old idea"},{"time":362920,"text":"called moir√© patterns."},{"time":364640,"text":"So the way that works is\nif you take two very, very fine patterns"},{"time":368120,"text":"and you move them across each other,"},{"time":369920,"text":"you will see a gross pattern"},{"time":372960,"text":"that a microscope can see"},{"time":375360,"text":"that otherwise you would not\nbe able to see."},{"time":377480,"text":"So he applied this technique\nto taking a really blurry image of a cell"},{"time":380800,"text":"and moving lots of structured\nlight patterns across it"},{"time":383400,"text":"until this cell became crystal clear."},{"time":386840,"text":"And here is the result:"},{"time":388880,"text":"a mysterious new world,"},{"time":391640,"text":"full of strange things zipping around"},{"time":393800,"text":"doing things that\nwe don't know what they're doing."},{"time":397600,"text":"But when we figure it out,\nwe'll have a better handle on life itself."}]},{"cues":[{"time":401600,"text":"For example, those\ngreen globs that you see?"},{"time":403720,"text":"Those things are called clathrins."},{"time":405960,"text":"They're molecules\nthat protect other molecules"},{"time":408400,"text":"as they move through a cell."},{"time":409800,"text":"Unfortunately, viruses sometimes\nhijack those to infect cells."},{"time":414160,"text":"Also, you see those little squiggly\nwormlike things moving around?"},{"time":417280,"text":"Those are actin molecules."},{"time":419600,"text":"Unfortunately, viruses\nalso climb down those things"},{"time":422040,"text":"to get into the cell nucleus"},{"time":423520,"text":"to replicate themselves and make you sick."}]},{"cues":[{"time":426240,"text":"Now that we can look at movies"},{"time":428120,"text":"of what's actually going on\ndeep inside a cell,"},{"time":431000,"text":"we have a much better chance\nof curing viral diseases like AIDS."}]},{"cues":[{"time":435680,"text":"So when you look at a movie like this,"},{"time":437560,"text":"it's very clear that Betzig has opened\nour eyes to a completely new world."},{"time":442560,"text":"But he hasn't shattered\nany cherished beliefs."}]},{"cues":[{"time":447200,"text":"That leads us to Dr. Aubrey de Grey"},{"time":450160,"text":"at Cambridge."},{"time":452440,"text":"De Grey definitely has scientists\nsquirming with an interesting idea:"},{"time":456800,"text":"we can be immortal."},{"time":458200,"text":"We can beat aging."},{"time":459840,"text":"Now, most scientists\nthink he's a crackpot."},{"time":463320,"text":"Any Biology 101 student knows"},{"time":466640,"text":"that aging is an inevitable\nconsequence of living."},{"time":470680,"text":"For example, when we eat,"},{"time":472800,"text":"we take in food and we metabolize it,"},{"time":474680,"text":"and that throws off\nwhat we call free radicals."},{"time":477080,"text":"You might have heard of those."},{"time":478560,"text":"Also known as oxygen ions,"},{"time":480520,"text":"those bind to our DNA, cause it to mutate,"},{"time":482920,"text":"and cause us to get old and lose our hair."}]},{"cues":[{"time":485000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":486600,"text":"It's just like, no, it's exactly like"},{"time":489360,"text":"oxygen binding to iron and making it rust."},{"time":491560,"text":"So you age because you rust out."}]},{"cues":[{"time":494040,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":496240,"text":"Oh, and scientists also know\nthere is something called immortality:"},{"time":501360,"text":"in cancer cells."},{"time":503360,"text":"So if you stop aging,"},{"time":505680,"text":"all of you are going to turn\ninto giant walking malignant tumors."}]},{"cues":[{"time":510680,"text":"These are cherished beliefs,\nbut could de Grey be on to something?"},{"time":515159,"text":"I think he deserves a closer look."},{"time":516840,"text":"First of all, I have a really hard time\nseeing him as a crackpot."},{"time":520000,"text":"Yeah, he started off life\nas a computer scientist,"},{"time":522360,"text":"not a biologist,"},{"time":523880,"text":"but he earned a PhD\nin biology from Cambridge,"},{"time":527720,"text":"and he has published\nsome very significant work"},{"time":530120,"text":"on mitochondrial DNA\nand a bunch of other stuff."},{"time":532600,"text":"Secondly, he started\nan antiaging foundation"},{"time":535720,"text":"that has identified\nseven different causes of aging,"},{"time":538320,"text":"to me, that seem very plausible,"},{"time":540600,"text":"and he is hot in pursuit\nof fixes for every single one of them."},{"time":544760,"text":"For example, one of the reasons we age\nis that our mitochondrial DNA mutates,"},{"time":549800,"text":"and we get kind of old\nand our cells lose energy."},{"time":553160,"text":"He believes, and he's made\na convincing case,"},{"time":555520,"text":"that using viruses we can do gene therapy,"},{"time":558080,"text":"fix that DNA"},{"time":559760,"text":"and rejuvenate our cells."}]},{"cues":[{"time":563400,"text":"One more thing."},{"time":564760,"text":"We have an existent proof"},{"time":566640,"text":"that extreme longevity is possible."},{"time":570520,"text":"Bristlecone pine trees live 5,000 years,"},{"time":575720,"text":"and some lobsters don't age at all."}]},{"cues":[{"time":580640,"text":"Now, this doesn't mean that de Grey\nis going to revolutionize our lifespans."},{"time":585000,"text":"I mean, after all, we're not trees,\nand most of us are not lobsters."}]},{"cues":[{"time":588840,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":590080,"text":"But I've got to believe that there are\nDarwins and Einsteins out there,"},{"time":595840,"text":"and I'll tell you why."},{"time":597240,"text":"Consider this:"},{"time":599160,"text":"there are seven times more people\nalive today than during Darwin's time."},{"time":604480,"text":"There are four times as many people\nalive today as Einstein."},{"time":607960,"text":"When you consider"},{"time":609200,"text":"that the proportion of scientists\nin the population has skyrocketed,"},{"time":612440,"text":"there are now seven million scientists."},{"time":614840,"text":"I've got to believe, and I do believe,\nthat there's one of them out there"},{"time":619720,"text":"who is working right now in obscurity"},{"time":622080,"text":"to rock our lives,\nand I don't know about you,"},{"time":624520,"text":"but I can't wait to be rocked."}]},{"cues":[{"time":626360,"text":"Thank you."}]},{"cues":[{"time":627640,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}